:YeastPathways_AERO-GLYCEROL-CAT-PWY
        a                   owl:NamedIndividual , obo:GO_0019563 ;
        rdfs:comment        "Under aerobic conditions, S. cerevisiae is able to utilize glycerol as a sole carbon and energy source. Glycerol degradation is a two-step process; the first step of glycerol phosphorylation occurs in the cytosol, then glycerol-3-phosphate enters the motichondrion where the second step of conversion to dihydroxyacetone is catalyzed |CITS:[191434]|. Dihydroxyacetone is then returned to the cytosol where it enters into either glycolysis or gluconeogenesis. The genes encoding the enzymes catalyzing glycerol catabolism, GUT1 and GUT2, are carbon source regulated; gene expression is repressed when cells are grown on fermentable carbon sources such as glucose and upregulated on non-fermentable carbon sources such as glycerol or ethanol |CITS:[191434]|, |CITS:[10536147]|, |CITS:[11142398]|. On non-fermentable carbon sources, GUT1 transcription is induced by the transcriptional activators Adr1p, Ino2p and Ino4p |CITS:[10536147]|, while GUT2 regulation requires the protein kinase Snf1p and the transcriptional activating Hap2p/Hap3p/Hap4p/Hap5p complex |CITS:[11142398]|. Conversely, the negative regulator Opi1p facilitates GUT1 and GUT2 repression |CITS:[10536147]|, |CITS:[11142398]|." ;
        rdfs:label          "glycerol degradation" ;
        dc:contributor      "GOC:sgd_curators" ;
        dc:date             "2023-09-14" ;
        pav:providedBy      "http://www.yeastgenome.org" ;
        oboInOwl:hasDbXref  "YeastPathways_AERO-GLYCEROL-CAT-PWY" ;
        skos:note           "org.biopax.paxtools.model.level3.Pathway" .

